Camille Auer wanted to correct her gender, was diagnosed with mental illness, and now she is making art on the subject - "A person should have the right to his own body"
Dozens of patient stories hang from the roof of the Academy of Fine Arts’ Project room gallery.
Each of them bears the name of Camille Auer.
The papers tell a multi-year story of how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
They decided for him who he was.
“I wanted to share my personal medical history to make the violence of the process visible,” Auer says.
She refers to the gender reassignment process.
It is often a period of years of research that includes meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process will begin with a referral to the diagnostics of "gender identity disorder" carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
In the case of Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, she had used the estrogen she had ordered over the internet and was already very advanced in her own repair process.
She felt that she was a woman, but under Finnish law, a person has to go through a correction process in order to be able to correct the gender legally as well.
The Trans Act (563/2002) obligates transgender people to undergo forced sterilization in order to obtain the correct gender, for example, in the Population Register Centre and in the passport.
At the moment, every person who corrects their gender requires a psychiatric diagnosis and a certificate of infertility.
A person has the right to control their own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," says Auer.
The reform of the Transla law has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has made eight observations on the law, and the European Court of Human Rights has a preliminary ruling obliging the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect the right to self-determination.
The previous Finnish Government prepared the amendment of the Act under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health Susanne Huovinen.
There were elections and the Finns Party took over the government.
Now the law is stuck again.
These are domestic disputes that do not even relate to this law.
“The government does not want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government about changing the law,” said Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty Finland.
The front part of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines used by Auer.
In the patient story installation, any visitor can read, for example, the transpol psychologist’s interpretation of Auer at Tampere University Hospital.
The psychologist met with Camille Auer twice and wrote a report that would define Auer’s right to care and help.
The perception of the reality under study appears prone to faltering.
The self-perception of the subject appears to be fragmented at the border space level, and the unstable features of the personality are highlighted.
Auer did not recognize himself from these descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed with mental illness," Auer says.
It was even more shocking when Auer was denied sex reassignment treatment.
According to the medical staff, his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his own identity.
Then, on February 11, 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked off the TV in the waiting room of the Transpol.
Later, a work of art called Monument for the Excluded was created from that television, in which Auer reflected on his experience of power and its use.
"It's crazy that anyone who is a woman at birth can enlarge their breasts, but to remove them, you need a diagnosis," Auer says.
Your body is not your own if you feel that you are not defined by your gender at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer’s experience is not the only one.
For many, the sex reassignment process is harder for mental reasons than purely medical operations.
Those going through it will meet dozens of people who need to justify their own existence and right to their own sexual experience.
“It’s crazy that people who need support and help are denied treatment on the grounds that they don’t have the resources,” Auer says.
Many of the participants in the process have psychological symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible experiences of bullying.
On the basis of these, the medical staff may order that treatment cannot be started.
“Preventing treatment and getting help can plunge a person into an even worse situation than it was before the process began,” Auer says.
Auer’s own exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition publication, Auer writes: "I have had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life, and that is something that people usually find difficult to digest."
Depression has been treated with medication, and when Auer started using hormones, I felt relieved.
She had finally been able to express feelings that had existed since childhood and adolescence.
Why the broad chin didn’t seem to fit my body and why the chest muscles had to be round instead of flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer has been that there are people around him who can see him.
To be seen is a basic need.
“You have to justify yourself so much by talking, getting dressed, using your voice and moving around,” she says.
Today, Auer feels that she is already visible, that she exists as a woman.
However, in the early stages of the process, random comments from loved ones could hurt a lot.
It hurts the most when people close to you misbehave.
“They should know and they know who I am, but they won’t accept or can’t internalize it,” he continues.
However, not all trans people need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, where the body or its parts can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and a long examination process, you can not get official confirmation of your own sex.
"There is no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And it's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014 the parliament approved a new procedure for the recognition of legal gender.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination with regard to legal gender.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identity code stating that he or she feels that he or she is of the opposite sex.
After a six-month period of reflection, the applicant confirms his/her application in writing and the Ministry gives the applicant a new personal identity code.
This right of self-determination is also required in Finland, and this requirement is also summed up in Auer’s exhibition.
It has not been a therapeutic experience for the artist; the exhibition is a collection of political and artistic works.
I want to believe that art still holds weight and can bring about political change at a time when politicians have forgotten about human rights.
