Civil Rights Organization issues travel warning to Missouri
The National Association for African-American Civil Rights (NAACP) has issued a travel alert for Missouri, following discriminatory practices and racist attacks in the state.
“NAACP’s Missouri Travel Notice, effective August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors, and locals to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling in a state that has recently witnessed a number of questionable racial events,” the agency said in a statement.
The recent Missouri law makes it difficult to bring cases of discrimination to court, and enforcement of state laws disproportionately affects minorities. According to the NAACP, these factors led to the issuing of a travel warning.
“People’s civil rights are being violated.
They are stopped for their skin color and beaten or killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP, told the Kansas City Star.
"We've never heard of so many cases in so short a time."
The Missouri travel bulletin is the organization’s first warning of a U.S. state.
The organization cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year when he was driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel and was arrested by the Missouri police even though he was not charged with a crime.
According to the Missouri Department of Justice, police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than a white one.
“The purpose of the travel bulletin is to urge people to be on their guard and to warn their families, friends, and coworkers about what might be happening in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to prepare, for example, by bringing in money to pay bail or telling relatives that they’re going to travel through the state.”
According to the FBI, one hundred hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, the 16th most in the United States.
The travel alert is also a response to Missouri’s new law, which makes it harder to sue companies for discrimination in housing and employment.
The ACLU recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they passed immigration laws obliging the police to arrest people for immigration offenses. According to the organization, this adds to racial profiling.
Generally, travel warnings are issued by the State Department and apply to other states, but recently they have been issued by NGOs in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
