Until recently, relations between the United States and Russia seemed to be moving from cold to warm.
US President Donald Trump and Russian President Vladimir Putin, who met at the G20 summit in Hamburg, seemed to get along well.
Since then, the atmosphere has cooled considerably.
Russia reacted bitterly to the new economic sanctions adopted by the US Congress last week and signed by Trump on Wednesday.
Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev has said the sanctions bill signed by Trump amounts to a “full-scale trade war.”
Even if Russia’s reactions were only political rhetorical aggravations and excesses, the tightening of relations between the United States and Russia is a fact after a short honeymoon period after Trump’s election.
In the United States, sanctions against Russia, Iran and North Korea were not easy to pass.
The Congress passed the law unanimously, but it was much more difficult for the President to pass the law.
Trump called the bill “significantly flawed.”
The reason for President Trump’s strutting may have been Russia in particular, although the passing of a law restricting one’s own powers must also have been repugnant.
As is well known, the United States is investigating both possible Russian interference in the presidential election and the Trump campaign’s ties to Russia.
Tensions between the United States and Russia are a fact after a short honeymoon.
As the White House staff has changed frequently and various scandalous developments have been revealed, it seems increasingly clear that foreign policy in the United States is not conducted under the leadership of the President, but in spite of the President.
Such a situation is by no means desirable.
If the relationship with Russia is complicated in the United States, the same applies to the European Union.
In addition to economic sanctions, the tense security situation in the EU's core region, the Baltic Sea, is tightening relations.
The EU has visibly highlighted the situation in Ukraine in its relations with Russia and called for the implementation of the Minsk Agreement.
Although the Union has so far remained, at least on the face of it, united in its policy towards Russia, the interests of the Member States are quite different.
For a member country like Finland that trades a lot with Russia, economic sanctions have been a real nuisance.
The effects of the recent US sanctions are still unclear.
The EU has feared that sanctions will make it more difficult for many European companies to operate.
In Finland, the effects may be felt, for example, in the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project and possibly in Fennovoima’s nuclear power plant project.
The acidity in Europe has been caused by the exclusion from the sanctions of LNG, which is important for the US economy, for example.
Trade sanctions are a means of expressing disapproval in world politics.
However, economic sanctions must be well thought out and carefully controlled.
Otherwise, they will easily do more harm than good.
Is nothing sacred anymore?
Trump’s White House now has the Statue of Liberty in its sights
Interference with statues is the surest sign of a change of power.
The Americans know this as well as anyone else: the Iraqis, together with American soldiers, demolished a statue of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the main ideologues of the Trump administration, was well aware of what was being done in the heated debate with CNN’s Jim Acosta. The Statue of Liberty was attacked by Miller in a spat about the president’s proposal to significantly reduce legal immigration.
Miller didn't exactly criticize the statue itself.
Had he done so, he would have been attacked by huge hordes of cruise organizers and figures imitating the Statue of Liberty.
His attack was on the significance of the statue and, in 1903, the poem by Emma Lazarus was added to the base of the statue – 17 years after the statue was completed.
This is how Miller chided Acosta: "I don't want to go into history now, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the whole world.
The poem was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller himself was not wrong, but it is not just history, as he himself said.
The words of Lazarus are the only ones of their kind in which the state calls not only the immigrants but the "poorest of the poor": "Your tired, your poor, / Your huddled masses yearning to breathe free, / The wreathed rebuke of your teaming shore."
The poem is now more relevant than ever.
Miller made it clear that the "poorest of the poor" are not welcome in Trump's United States.
The controversy over the importance of the Statue of Liberty is part of a broader political and cultural controversy over the importance of the United States.
After his death, Lazarus’ friends campaigned to have the poem fastened to the base of the statue, knowing full well that it was a strongly political act.
The purpose of the statue was to express the connections between French and American republicanism through the classical symbol, the feminine embodiment of freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, but has a voice.
And it gives itself a new name: the mother of the exiles.
Attaching the poem to the image was an ingenious feminist coup d'état and a devastating attack on the American nationalist ideal.
Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, and the right has long wanted to change it back to the original.
Rush Limbaugh – a mouthpiece that can now be seen as some sort of harbinger of Trump – claimed in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty is not an invitation to anyone, but is an early pioneer of neoconservatives who take the torch of the United States to a world covered in darkness: “Lady Liberty steps forward.
He takes the freedom of the torch from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch does not point the way to the United States."
Rarely, Limbaugh was partially right.
The significance of the Statue of Liberty depends entirely on perspective.
Lazarus saw it as the poor and weary but hopeful immigrants from the deck of a ship after a long and trying journey.
He saw it from the perspective of people looking for shelter and a better life.
His Statue of Liberty comforts us by giving hope and welcoming us.
That’s not what Miller and Trump want.
Their torch does not point the way, but kindles the flames of hatred, their only source of strength.
