Blocking reviewers on Facebook: Don’t run for public office if you can’t stand criticism
The father of our country knew what bad publicity was.
The Americans loved George Washington, but newspapers soon began to criticize him for everything from possible domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism is annoying,
But he did not silence his critics.
“If freedom of speech is taken away, we may be led dumb and silent as sheep to the slaughter,” Washington said in 1783.
Which brings us to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should learn from Washington.
Hogan’s staff has removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and blocked those who posted them.
The U.S. Civil Liberties Union sued Hogan earlier this week.
His staff consider the challenge unfounded, and the attitude was also belittling online.
"What does it matter? This is just Facebook," many commenters said.
But it does matter,
Especially in the case of Hogan.
Hogan is the surprisingly popular Republican governor of a Democratic-controlled state.
He has received the second highest rating among the 50 governors.
Hogan's not very responsive to hotheads.
He has led the state firmly and has stood firm on principles.
He has also skillfully used Facebook as the main channel of communication with his voters and published there a picture of a balding head in chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking users from coming to the governor's Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous. The governor's page is a public and official forum, which is maintained by his staff with tax funds.
Hogan's spokesman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor's actions in an interview with the Washington Post, saying it was just a matter of moderation.
However, labeling commenters as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy a solution.
The Washington Post interviewed users blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to leaders of their choice; they were not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs and pastors, for example.
They reported that their comments were respectful, considerate, and businesslike.
In his comment, the pastor quoted the Bible; he wanted to appeal to Hogan’s Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Maryland, was not hostile but asked a question about hate crimes.
“I politely commented that I was disappointed that Hogan had not taken a stand on hate crimes and other recent news,” he wrote in a Washington Post commentary.
"I also cannot accept that when more people comment on the same issue, they are immediately seen as a sort of organised group, and that a large group of concerned citizens is ignored."
The governor's staff called the comments a "concentrated attack." Someone else might call them to advance matters of importance.
In the age of Facebook, it’s easy to manage communication by blocking a reviewer or deleting a critical comment.
In the old days, we should have sent staff to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or to arrest and silence demonstrators.
It’s the same thing, only digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be charged with shackling Facebook and other social media channels.
Twitter users blocked by President Trump have sued him.
The first major decision was made in Virginia last week.
Alexandria District Judge James C. Cacheris said the Loudoun County government violated the First Amendment by blocking voters on Facebook.
And the U.S. Civil Liberties Union went to discuss the use of Twitter and Facebook with Kentucky Republican Governor Matt Bevin.
This shouldn't be difficult.
In the time of Washington, low postage had an effect similar to that of the Internet today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and Washington was hammered by anonymous writers.
There were trolls then.
The pseudonyms Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius wrote letters in the newspapers defaming Washington's decisions.
The President’s office was flooded with petitions criticising the Jay Agreement, a cooperation, trade and shipping agreement between the United States and the United Kingdom, as evidenced by documents collected by the Papers of George Washington online project.
But he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of expression, freedom of opinion and freedom of debate are the cornerstones of our nation.
True leadership means accepting this fact.
The summer feeding of birds should be stopped immediately
Samples have come from about half a dozen places, and also online notifications from two or three.
Most of them have come from Southern and Southwest Finland, but also from Haapavesi and Seinäjoki, says Senior Scientist Marja Isomursu from Evira.
Green finches have died from a parasitic disease called trichomoniasis.
It is caused by a protozoa called Trichomonas gallinae.
In the past, it has been known to strike pigeons, especially the poodle.
However, in the 21st century, the disease was also observed in finches.
In 2009 it hit hard.
At that time, trichomoniasis caused a big collapse in the Finnish greenfinch population, after which the population of the species has been recovering.
There have now been sick green finches, but at least not yet on a large scale, says Juha Honkala, Museum Master at the University of Helsinki’s Central Museum of Natural Sciences (Luomus).
It is feared that the previous epidemic of green finches will reoccur if nothing is done.
What needs to be done now is a very simple thing that anyone can do: stop summer feeding birds immediately.
More on that later.
