Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Land of Gold
Bardina Degei does not use a stove in cooking.
He rarely uses a pot, too.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in the troubled province of Papua, Indonesia. When he cooks dinner, he usually puts the sweet potato – locally “nota” – directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred sweet potato is eaten greedily with bare, unwashed hands.
There is no furniture in Degei’s home, and he sits on a muddy earth floor, where he usually does his daily chores, such as washing his clothes in the muddy water from a nearby swamp.
There is a bucket in the ceiling-free room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband’s four wives, and she is not assigned to tend the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many are drinking heavily.
"No one dares to walk in the village after five in the evening," Degei says.
This is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed by Indonesia in 1969, following a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed Dutch rule, quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta government, which is tightly controlling the region and blocking access to foreign journalists and human rights monitors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
The journey to Enarotal starts with an hour-and-a-half flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and continues with a stomach-wrenching five-hour drive in a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
With a population of about 19,000, the city has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, with corrugated roofs stained with yellowish brown by rust.
Few Indonesians have ever been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the advent of the Christian missionaries, the Papuan Mee Pago tribesmen worshiped the god Uga Tamee.
Other changes have taken place.
“We didn’t have clothes like this,” Degei says. He means his colorful, hand-woven wrap-up headdress, dark skirt, and brightly colored blouse.
“Before, we only had leaves to cover our bodies.”
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and one of the highest rates of child mortality and illiteracy in Asia.
But it is also the gold of Indonesia.
Paniai is a highland area about the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000. Just about 100 kilometers from Paniai is Grasberg, the largest and most profitable gold mine in the world. It is owned by the Freeport McMoran company, headquartered in Phoenix, USA.
In 2015, the mine generated $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in wood reserves.
For the Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, as they mean the suffocating presence of a strong Indonesian army.
The New York Times reported in 2005 that Freeport paid local military personnel and local units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004.
Papua's demands for greater self-determination threaten this source of income and are mercilessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, since 1969, the Indonesian army has killed more than 500,000 Papuans and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the massacres in the highlands of the Papuan tribes in the 1970s amounted to genocide.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the area during peaceful demonstrations.
The Brisbane Archdiocese’s 2016 We Will Lose Everything report includes reports of last year’s atrocities, including extrajudicial executions, torture – rape and electric shocks are particularly popular means – and relentless attacks on peaceful protests.
“Calculating the number of victims is difficult because there are cases every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher with Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been tightened as Papua’s natural resources attract migrants from elsewhere in Indonesia.
Eighty-three percent of the province’s 3.5 million inhabitants are Christian, but the population is changing as Indonesia’s populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi migrate to the region in search of a better livelihood for Muslims.
Javanese warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado-vegetable mix in peanut sauce.
Locals find it hard to compete.
"The movers have started selling chicken and vegetables at the market for less than the locals," said Abeth You, a 24-year-old from Paniai who moved to the provincial capital for work.
"Local women lost their customers."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – promised in his 2014 election campaign to address Papua’s injustices and human rights violations.
Papua is made up of 29 regions, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 regions, including Pania, on his way to Jakarta’s Presidential Palace.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokow in 2014 and expected him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice," You said.
Panic was felt only two months after Jokow’s October inauguration.
Eleven children were singing Christmas carols by a campfire in Enarotal on 7 December 2014, when two Indonesian soldiers appeared from the dark on motorcycles.
The frightened children told the soldiers that they should use the headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned with four soldiers.
According to the accounts of the victims and the Witnesses, drunken soldiers took the children and beat them with rifle butts.
So one of the soldiers shot at the children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, fell into a coma as a result of the assault.
A few hours later, the building of the State Electoral Commission near the scene was set on fire, and the next day began to happen.
