New results of Swedish age tests for asylum seekers announced
The latest results of the Swedish asylum-seekers’ medical age tests have been published. The results of the tests carried out using the new assessment method reveal that more than 80% of those tested were determined to be over 18 years of age. However, not everyone considers the tests to be reliable.
The Swedish National Bureau of Forensic Science started testing earlier this year.
The new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to determine the actual age of applicants who claimed to be minors.
So far, the Finnish Immigration Service has carried out 6,880 tests, and the Forensic Service has now published the results of 2,481 tests. The tests were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
Eighty per cent of those tested, i.e. in 2002, were determined to be over 18 years of age. In addition, in 25 cases, the Forensic Office determined that the test subject was “possibly 18 years of age or older”.
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker was "possibly under the age of 18".
Tests were carried out only in cases where there was reason to doubt the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan G<0xC3><0xB6>ransson of the Forensic Science Office says the results are in line with those of previous months.
"The figures are quite consistent. There are no big differences to the statistics for the previous months," he told The Local.
Although a large proportion of applicants were determined to be over the age of 18, this does not necessarily mean that applicants have lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, there were “suggestions that the subject is 18 years of age or older.”
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases, the applicant had openly stated that he would turn 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes X-rays of wisdom teeth and magnetic images of the knee joint. Then dentists and radiologists analyze the images. The method has also been criticized.
One of the sceptics is the endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institutet, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans. The assessment can help determine whether a person has entered puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I have had reason to think about it, and I believe that the method used is not the right one.
Determining the biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't determine for sure the age, we shouldn't pretend that we can," he told Metro.
However, G<0xC3><0xB6>ransson of the Forensic Science Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "Generally speaking, the risk of determining a child as an adult is small.
The risk is highest in a situation where the test subject will soon turn 18 years old, and then the risk is about 10 percent."
