How did one activist learn to answer the question: To whom do the streets belong?
Brittany Ferrell was shocked on August 9, 2014.
He had arrived in New York the day before from his home in St. Louis and was sitting on the bed in his Airbnb apartment, browsing Facebook on his phone.
Then he noticed a message from his high school friend:
“The police just killed an 18-year-old young man, and his body is still on the street.”
Confused, he noticed that no one else had posted the same information in his feed, so he shut down Facebook and opened Twitter.
His timeline had numerous retweets from <0x40>TheePharoah.
The username belongs to a rapper in St. Louis who tweeted in real time about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man who was shot dead by white police in Ferguson, Missouri.
The user had also posted a photo of Brown’s lifeless body on the street, where it was left for four hours.
"This is incredible," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to him and his community.
When he returned to Twitter later that night, it was reported that people were gathering at Canfield Drive.
Users posted pictures of police deadlocks and screaming people, as well as a man claiming to be Brown’s father, who carried a sign that read, “Ferguson Police just killed my unarmed son!”
Ferrell watched a live video of police standing in front of the protesters with a barking dog.
He also said he saw a video of another police officer arming his rifle and shouting, “I’m going to kill all of you...animals.”
"This is not normal," Ferrell recalled.
"It wasn't the kind of murder we're used to and could be said to be typical.
That's when I felt the chills.
I was angry and crying.”
He booked a return flight home the next day.
Ferrell went to pick up his six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that they would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next nearly three years has been made into a documentary film called "Whose Streets?", which premiered in cinemas on August 11, 2017.
The film is a story of survival and expression, love and loss, and strength and perseverance from the perspective of the local people who took to the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove toward Ferguson with his daughter in a flower dress and matching crown, they had a renewed conversation about "what it's like to be black and under what circumstances" and had spoken about it countless times before that morning.
"Remember when I told you how black people have had to fight for the things they believe in?" Ferrell remembers saying to his daughter.
"We're going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it's not right."
"I couldn't take my daughter with me," Ferrell said.
“Today’s events are the culmination of the past.
My daughter has a right to know it and to grow up with it.
He needs to be prepared for activism and organization, but he also needs to know the different layers and circumstances of the experience of being black, and he needs to know what we need to do to liberate ourselves.
Although I have been fortunate enough to be able to protect her from blatant racism, she is still the same as other black girls.
I feel that I would harm him if I protected him from reality.”
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, across the street from the police station, which became a camp for activists as they waited for information about the case and eventually learned that no charges would be brought against the police.
From there, Ferrell and his daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to the protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to take a new approach to activism.
“My activism completely changed after August 9th,” he says. While studying at the University of Missouri in St. Louis, Ferrell was president of the Association of Minority Nursing Students. At the time, he focused on food law and health disparities in black communities.
“I didn’t have any experience in organizing.
Somehow it just happened.”
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, the documentary's assistant director, at an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and photographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "simply wanted to tell us" what was happening.
Ferrell was suspicious, and he said, "Do you really want to tell me what's going on, or do you want a story that you can use?"
The reason for the suspicion was the countless times when people, usually white people, had appeared in the local community, who only wanted to benefit from its difficulties and perseverance.
"We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson had no common voice," Folayan said in a recent interview. "We wanted to do things differently."
Folayan had already contacted assistant director Damon Davis, known for his activism with death row inmates.
Davis' involvement prompted Ferrell to join the project, along with six other locals, and the film crew followed the events in the years following Brown's shooting.
“This is not a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, but we speak for ourselves,” Davis said.
“The most important thing for me was how the local people are presented in the film, because I am presented in the same way.”
According to Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, as it was to show that the popular movement "is not about a charismatic leader, but about a community".
That’s why the documentary shows surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell’s life, such as falling in love and getting married.
“I felt pretty naked,” Ferrell laughs as he describes what it felt like to see the movie for the first time.
"But I realized that this work and the human portrayal of blacks requires a certain vulnerability."
