A fitting resemblance: an artist creates portraits of Chelsea Manning’s DNA
At the Fridman Gallery in New York City, faces are hung in the middle of the exhibition space – white, black and brown faces, between which, if you look closely, you can see a resemblance.
These 30 works are portraits by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg, based on DNA samples taken from Chelsea Manning’s cheek and hair.
Manning sent samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where he served a 35-year sentence for leaking classified diplomatic cables to WikiLeaks.
Dewey-Hagborg’s exhibition A Becoming Resemblance opened on 2 August 2017.
Dewey-Hagborg is a trans woman and a pioneering dissident, whose prison sentence was commuted by Barack Obama on the third and final day of his term in office.
Dewey-Hagborg analysed Manning’s DNA algorithmically and created 30 portraits based on his genetic data. They are a sharp, albeit somewhat theoretical, statement on the editability, ambiguity, and causal relationships behind interpretations of DNA data, as well as identity.
Chelsea Manning, born Bradley Edward, has openly stated that she has identified with women since puberty and was found guilty of 20 crimes in 2013, including espionage, computer fraud and theft.
There was only one picture of Manning in prison: a grainy, black-and-white selfie with the awkward-looking Manning sitting in the car in the driver’s seat, wearing a platinum-white wig that became his signature.
Dewey-Hagborg had a successful Stranger Visions project in 2015, which he carried out in 2012.
In it, he created portraits based on forensic data, such as DNA data from cigarette butts and chewing gum, and created images of what the people involved might have looked like.
Then the artist received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning and needed a picture for their story," Dewey-Hagborg told a news conference for the new show.
Manning was not allowed to visit or be photographed in prison, so the magazine contacted Chelsea and asked if she would be interested in making a DNA portrait of Manning.
The artist and his imprisoned muse suddenly became pen pals, writing to each other for a couple of years.
They even co-authored the Suppressed Images comic book, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, depicting a future in which the president would have commuted Chelsea’s sentence and she would be able to see the show.
In reality, Obama reduced Manning's sentence just a few days after the publication of the comic book, which was a lucky coincidence after seven hard years in a Kansas military prison.
It is also impressive that the exhibition opens right now, as Donald Trump is waging his own war against whistleblowers and transgender soldiers and inventing ever-new ways on Twitter to reinforce the powerful dichotomy he actually needed to bridge.
Dewey-Hagborg believes that “everything has a purpose.”
On the wall of the gallery is a statement by the artist and below it a large autograph of Manning, where the point of the surname i is the heart. In his statement, the artist demands an end to the "automatic division on which gender, race, sexuality and culture have been based".
On the opposite wall is a sequence of Manning's DNA: a long string of C, G, and A's written in pencil.
With this combination of 200 letters – or nucleotides, as the artist uses the scientific definition – Dewey-Hagborg wants to illustrate how similar we all are, at least in our biology.
"I hope that my exhibition will help people to understand that we are equal in our genetic heritage and that the genetic information is very personal and open to interpretation," says Dewey-Hagborg.
"DNA tells countless stories. 30 of them are on display here."
The last work in the exhibition is in its own room: a page from Manning’s and Dewey-Hagborg’s comic book.
In it, Manning’s character emerges from prison like King Kong, holding a megaphone.
“If they can silence you, they’ve won,” the caption reads.
"Never be silent."
"The text is from a letter I got from Manning," a Philadelphia-based artist said.
"It's so impressive that I'm still getting cold flashes."
Contrary to what was described in the comic book, Manning has not yet seen the exhibition. When Manning arrives, he is greeted by a face based on his own genetic information, like a crowd of demonstrators in the middle of the exhibition space.
It is intentional, like everything else in this exhibition: for example, Manning’s DNA sequence is written in pencil at a height equal to his height (157.5 cm).
“The face was on the wall before, but I wanted to bring a crowd feeling to it,” Dewey-Hagborg says.
"I wanted to describe the mass movement that Chelsea created, which was also behind her release."
