It also recently signed an agreement with Uber.
Like Glint, Convercent enables companies to conduct customized surveys, gather responses confidentially in real time, and identify problem areas.
In addition, employees can report inappropriate behaviour anonymously via SMS.
And if there is reason to suspect the manager of misconduct, complaints go directly to the board of directors of the company.
“Public opinion has supplanted the authorities,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
He points out that if a company treats its employees badly or unethically, the consequences can be costly, even if the authorities do not intervene; consumers can start boycotting the company, and it can also lose employees and be sued.
