The Birth of a Comic Book: The Story of a Castle
The small Scotney Castle in Kent County is now known from Squeeze's music video and as Margaret Thatcher's hideout from the 1970s and 1980s.
With 700 years of turbulent history behind it, this charming castle in the Bewlin River Valley is the subject of a comic book by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired author who has long been fond of old documents.
“I am delighted to be able to study a text written by a person who died more than 300 years ago,” Rhodes said.
"I feel a personal connection when I hold a letter in my hand."
The book A Castle in England, by Rhodes, tells the stories of families living in Scotland from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period, each illustrated by a different artist, a promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first archival book. In 2014, he published Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, inspired by documents from the British National Library. The project was emotional.
"I was moved to tears when I saw the thumbprint in the letter, written by a double agent who worked for the Jacobites in the 18th century," Rhodes says.
"It was his fingerprints!
And the letters smell like smoke, because at that time fire was used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the scent makes the reader feel like he or she is on the spot.
I love the archives!
With the support of the National Trust and the National Council for the Arts in England, the writer was able to live in the castle for almost four months, which seemed too good to be true.
He spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, archives, treasures and rarities, such as hyena heads hung on walls and bottles in a moat for centuries.
He toured the ruins and estates of the old castle and talked with foresters, gardeners, and sometimes even artists illustrating the book.
In the evenings he took a scotch and began to write.
Scotney's more recent history is unknown, as the castle did not become a part of the National Trust until the death of its last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about ten years later, the staff of the foundation was just beginning to go through the archives. Rhodes describes that the archives had been kept for hundreds of years by the same method: taking everything extra to the attic.
There were diaries in the archives, letters from the times of the English Empire and maps of who owned what. "You could imagine that land disputes are boring," Rhodes says. "Here, however, families fought even for one birch.
I thought we should let it go already.”
Some of the stories in the book progress from the castle to English history, such as The Labourer, about a man who joined the English Peasants' Revolt in 1381 shortly after the completion of the castle.
"The Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex mentions that there was a riot in the castle in 1380," Rhodes said.
“The English peasant revolt began in the same area, and it occurred to me that the revolt could begin with a riot.
“Perhaps these events are related?”
The other stories in the book are closely related to the history of the castle – such as The Priest, a story about a priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
The Smuggler, on the other hand, tells the story of the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is said to have staged his own funeral by filling his coffin with stones (it was discovered years later when his tomb was opened).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family in Scotney. "The men in the family seem to have been quite the villains. They were constantly going into debt and buying things they could not afford.
The men of the Darrell family solved their debt problem by marrying wealthy old women, and I see them as handsome men who could court heiresses."
Now Rhodes is looking for new writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in Finland writing a comic book about Elämänmäki, a sanatorium that operated at the beginning of the 20th century.
Scotney Castle holds a special place in his heart.
“It was sad to leave,” he said.
“I didn’t want to go back to this damn place.”
