Red Meat, Dairy, and Chocolate May Alleviate Irritable Bowel Syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like the nightmares of the digestive system.
However, a recent study suggests the opposite: a diet high in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 people in the United Kingdom. It causes stomach cramps, swelling, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People with irritable bowel syndrome are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps the body to develop immune cells that strengthen intestinal tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, the study’s director, the immune cells guard the swamp and ensure that no harmful microbes hiding in food enter the body.
Inflammatory cells are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to inflammation, IBS can result.
In the experiments, it was found that immune cells that strengthen the tolerability are present in mice with a specific bacterium in the intestine.
The bacterium in question needs tryptophan to start producing immune cells. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
"We found a link between the development of Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote tolerance. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal microbiome of the gut," says Professor Colonna.
"The more tryptophan was in the diet of mice, the more they had such immune cells."
If the same works in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce susceptibility to inflammation.
When investigating immune cells that strengthen tolerance, postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they did not have them in mice of the same species, which were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the mice’s gut microbiome, the normal gastrointestinal tract community of bacteria, fungi, and viruses.
When the mice’s intestinal DNA was examined, six species of bacteria were found in mice with immune cells, but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was given to mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have the gut microbiome and did not develop immune cells, they began to develop immune cells.
The researchers wanted to find out how the bacteria affect the immune system by growing Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in liquids and transferring small amounts of liquid – without bacteria – to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells developed into tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the number of tolerance-enhancing cells increased by about 50 percent. When the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells fell to half of what it had been before.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same cells that strengthen tolerance as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether tryptophan by-products from Lactobacillus reuteri cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, tryptophan-related gene defects have been observed in IBS patients.
"We probably want to promote the development of such cells, because they regulate inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines," says Cervantes-Barragan.
