White House spokesman: 'I wouldn't say it was a lie'
The White House admits that the two phone calls mentioned by US President Donald Trump never happened, according to the New York Times.
Trump’s phone calls with both the Mexican president and the leader of the scout organization have turned out to be made up.
White House spokeswoman Sarah Huckabee Sanders confirmed that no calls had been made.
But he said Trump wasn’t lying.
According to Sanders, many of the scout leaders spoke to Trump personally, and with Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto, Trump had spoken at the G20 summit in Hamburg.
I wouldn't say it was a lie, it's a pretty strong accusation.
“Those conversations happened, they didn’t just happen over the phone, they happened face-to-face,” Sanders said.
The speech to the scouts provoked outrage
Trump said on Monday that the Mexican president had called him and praised Trump’s success in eradicating illegal immigration.
According to Trump, Pena Nieto said few will come across Mexico’s southern border because they know the trip will stop at the U.S. border anyway.
The Mexican government issued a statement on Wednesday saying that the call had not been made.
On Tuesday, Politico released a full version of Trump’s interview with The Wall Street Journal.
In it, Trump extolled his speech at the National Scouting Association’s major meeting in West Virginia.
I got a call from the head of the Boy Scouts, he said it was the greatest speech ever given to them.
“They were very grateful,” Trump said.
On Wednesday, the organization said it was not aware of any calls to Trump from any of its leaders.
According to the statement, Michael Surbaugh’s earlier statement, in which he had apologized to the Boy Scouts for Trump’s speech, speaks for itself.
Trump’s speech at the Scout meeting was highly controversial, as it was unusually political in nature.
Among other things, he praised the results of last autumn’s presidential elections.
